== 6. b4 ==
This is by far White's best option. Black must now respond accurately.

'''6...cxb4?''' is sub-optimal. It seems that Black hopes to make use of a potential discovered attack after pushing their pawn, but this opportunity won't present itself after 7. Nb5! Nc6 8. axb4 Bxb4+ 9. c3 {{Chess/not|++}} as seen in Topalov - Ermenkov, Elenite 1994.<ref>{{cite web 
|url=https://lichess.org/jlKTRU40
|title=Topalov - Ermenkov, Elenite 1994
|website=lichess.org
|access-date=9 February 2026
}}</ref> White got to trade off the dark-squared bishops and place their knight on d6, where it can't be contested by pawns.

Instead, '''6...cxd4''' should be played, exchanging the c-pawn for White's central pawn and attacking the knight on c3. This is known as the '''Armenian line'''<ref>{{cite web
|url=https://www.chess.com/openings/French-Defense-Winawer-Advance-Retreat-Variation-Armenian-Line
|title=French Defense: Winawer, Advance, Retreat Variation, Armenian Line
|website=chess.com
|access-date=9 February 2026
}}</ref>, named after its use by Armenian grandmasters [[w:Rafael Vaganian|Rafael Vaganian]] and [[w:Smbat Lputian|Smbat Lputian]].<ref>{{cite book
|title=The French Defence: a Complete Black Repertoire
